## Please let us know what you&#39;ve done ##

First of all you need to share your work, that you&#39;ve made so far, so that we don&#39;t solve your issue totally on our own, but point you in the right direction.

## Solution + explanation ##

Alright, here&#39;s some tricky solutions. I assume that you need to do these things at the same time: 

 1. validate 2 necessary parameters, `username` and `email`; 
 2. check whether no other keys are included in request body.

Using `body()` with no parameters allows you to validate the whole **body** object.
 
Here&#39;s some info about it: [Whole body validation][1]

The code listed below is an example of API endpoint `POST /login` that does what you need. Please refer to the third validator in middlewares array (`body().custom(...)`).

    const { Router } = require(&#39;express&#39;);
    const router = Router();
    const { body, validationResult } = require(&#39;express-validator&#39;);
    
    router.post(&#39;/login&#39;, [
        body(&#39;username&#39;).isString().not().isEmpty(),
        body(&#39;email&#39;).isEmail(),
        body().custom(body =&gt; {
            const keys = [&#39;username&#39;, &#39;email&#39;];
            return Object.keys(body).every(key =&gt; keys.includes(key));
        }).withMessage(&#39;Some extra parameters are sent&#39;)
    ], (req, res, next) =&gt; {
        const errors = validationResult(req);
        if (!errors.isEmpty()) return res.status(422).send(errors.array({ onlyFirstError: true }))
        next();
    }, (req, res) =&gt; {
        //some other stuff
        res.status(200).send(&quot;OK&quot;)
    });

You can also substitute the third validator with this one:

    body().custom((body, { req }) =&gt; {
       const keys = [&#39;username&#39;, &#39;email&#39;];
       return Object.keys(req.body).every(key =&gt; keys.includes(key));
    }).withMessage(&#39;Some extra parameters are sent&#39;)

The only difference is that in this case you use `req` object, which you can always get in all `custom()` validators. This feature is described here: [Custom validation][2]

&gt; Receives the value of the field being validated, as well as the express request, the location and the field path.

## Results ##

Here I would like to share some screenshots that display `/login` endpoint behaviour:

 1. [No data was sent in request body][3];
 2. [Request body is (also) filled with unwanted keys][4];
 3. [Request body is filled correctly][5].


  [1]: https://express-validator.github.io/docs/whole-body-validation.html
  [2]: https://express-validator.github.io/docs/validation-chain-api.html#customvalidator
  [3]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/VlcQe.png
  [4]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/yQqmX.png
  [5]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/Wjjo8.png

